# Testing

## Running tests

```bash
make check    # full suite with branch coverage
make lint     # ruff + pyright only (no tests)
```

To run tests alone without the full gate: `uv run pytest`{% if python == 'component' %} (from within `{{ component_dir }}/`){% endif %}.

## Layout

```
tests/
  conftest.py              # shared fixtures
  test_imports.py          # architectural boundary enforcement
  {{ package_name }}/      # mirrors src/{{ package_name }}/ — one test file per module
  integration/             # tests that cross a real I/O boundary (db, filesystem, network)
```

**Module tests** (`tests/{{ package_name }}/`) mirror the production package. A test for `src/{{ package_name }}/foo.py` lives at `tests/{{ package_name }}/test_foo.py`.

**Integration tests** (`tests/integration/`) touch real external resources — database connections, real files, real HTTP. Never use mocks at these boundaries; mocks hide the very failures you want to catch.

Keep module tests free of I/O. If a test needs a file, socket, or database, it belongs in `integration/`.

## Dependency-direction tests

`tests/test_imports.py` enforces import boundaries via AST analysis. Populate the `BOUNDARIES` list with one entry per architectural boundary:

```python
BOUNDARIES: list[tuple[str, str]] = [
    ("db", "{{ package_name }}.cli"),   # db must not import from cli
    ("db", "{{ package_name }}.api"),   # db must not import from api
]
```

Each entry is `(source_layer, forbidden_import_prefix)`. A single parametrized test covers all of them.

## Fixtures

- Define fixtures in `conftest.py` at the appropriate scope (root for shared, subdirectory for local).
- Prefer function scope. Use session scope only for expensive, genuinely read-only resources.

## Coverage

Target: branch coverage over `{{ src_root }}/{{ package_name }}`. Config is in `pyproject.toml`. HTML report lands in `htmlcov/` after `make check`. The gate is 80% — the build fails below this threshold.

Exclude deliberately unreachable branches with `# pragma: no cover`.

## Test ordering

`pytest-randomly` randomises test execution order on every run. This catches hidden test interdependencies early. The seed is printed at the start of each run; use `--randomly-seed=<N>` to reproduce a specific order.
